<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14376">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b> The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and
      downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Chess.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14400">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14400 mb-requirement-id-14401">
        (a) Discuss with your counselor the history of the game of chess.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/YeB-1F-UKO0" target="_blank"
          >A Brief History of Chess (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14400 mb-requirement-id-14402">
        (b) Research a famous chess player and what accomplishments made him or
        her famous. Discuss with your counselor. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/TW0yJYab5YA" target="_blank"
          >Story of World Chess Champion Magnus Carlsen! (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/1DgosX9_T2U" target="_blank"
          >The 'Queen of Chess' Who Defeated Kasparov (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/GPuazOwq0aw" target="_blank"
          >Chess Champ Bobby Fischer on 60 Minutes (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14377">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      Discuss with your counselor the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14377 mb-requirement-id-14378">
        (a) Why chess is considered a game of planning and strategy. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/4CVIO3Ey2_Y" target="_blank"
          >Why Every Strategist Should Learn Chess (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14377 mb-requirement-id-14379">
        (b) The benefits of playing chess, including developing critical
        thinking skills, concentration skills, and decision-making skills, and
        how these skills can help you in other areas of your life. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/fyzWEXakASs" target="_blank"
          >14 Shocking Benefits of Playing Chess (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14377 mb-requirement-id-14403">
        (c) Sportsmanship and chess etiquette <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/C5LNdtayoKI" target="_blank"
          >The Morals of Chess by Benjamin Franklin (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/71wh24-AYZk" target="_blank"
          >Chess Etiquette (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.tiktok.com/@norwaychess/video/7524741028805430550"
          target="_blank"
          >Understanding Resignation and Respect in Chess (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14380">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Demonstrate to your counselor that you know each of the following. Then,
      using Scouting EDGE to teach someone who does not know how to play chess:
      <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a
        href="https://www.scouting.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/Teaching-Edge-Method.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >The EDGE Method of Teaching (PDF)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14380 mb-requirement-id-14381">
        (a) The name of each chess piece <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/f8LOIdpLWIk" target="_blank"
          >Chess 101: Name the Pieces (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14380 mb-requirement-id-14382">
        (b) How to set up a chessboard <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/NPyuNpYfrDc" target="_blank"
          >How to Set Up the Chess Board (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14380 mb-requirement-id-14383">
        (c) How each chess piece moves and captures, including: four rules of
        castling, en passant captures, pawn promotion, check, ways to get out of
        check, and checkmate. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/RpbQjiJ5ops" target="_blank"
          >How to Move the Chess Pieces? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/1Ut3Zw61v9M" target="_blank"
          >Chess: Castling and En Passant (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/C6bqDvAZVTk" target="_blank"
          >Check! | Chess Term (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Svswkqslr9I" target="_blank"
          >Checkmate | Chess Terms (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14380 mb-requirement-id-14404">
        (d) The five ways a game can end in a draw <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/rjHCE3UQY8w" target="_blank"
          >Draw and Stalemate in Chess Explained (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14384">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14384 mb-requirement-id-14385">
        (a) Demonstrate scorekeeping using the algebraic system of chess
        notation. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/mADPCw-rhPI" target="_blank"
          >Learn How To Record Your Chess Games, Read Books and Communicate
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14384 mb-requirement-id-14386">
        (b) Discuss the differences between the opening, the middle game, and
        the endgame. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/OYevDf-oCt0" target="_blank"
          >What Is a Chess Opening? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/mkOntF0rmSg" target="_blank"
          >The Dreaded Middlegame (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/UL8Jo4lc1Ms" target="_blank"
          >What Is the Endgame in Chess? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/cheyUEMgWDg" target="_blank"
          >A Beginner's Guide to Chess: Opening, Middlegame, and Endgame
          Principles (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14384 mb-requirement-id-14387">
        (c) Explain four opening principles. Demonstrate for your counselor the
        first five moves of the following openings: Ruy Lopez, French Defense,
        Queen's Gambit Declined, Sicilian Defense. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/nx2HKfOHRBM" target="_blank"
          >The Ruy Lopez: The Opening Every Chess Player Must Know (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/vOw5BQYCfWA" target="_blank"
          >The French Defense Chess Opening Explained in 4 Minutes by a Chess
          Master! (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ZEQWwuAa2-o" target="_blank"
          >Learn the Queen's Gambit Declined (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/qzydxPgPKzs" target="_blank"
          >Chess Openings: Sicilian Defense (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14384 mb-requirement-id-14388">
        (d) On a chessboard, demonstrate Scholar's Mate, Fool's Mate, Légal
        Mate, Fried Liver Attack, and Noah's Ark Trap. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/jrUalgPaiPQ" target="_blank"
          >Fools Mate Scholar's Mate and a Nice Tactic (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iEu3xT--f_k" target="_blank"
          >Legal's Mate Trap: Chess Opening Trick To Fool Your Opponent &amp;
          Win Fast (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/EmYD8v81BY8" target="_blank"
          >The Fried Liver Attack in 1 Minute (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/KskXvXxlkCM" target="_blank"
          >Chess Trap: Noah's Ark Trap—Guy Lopez (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14391">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14391 mb-requirement-id-14392">
        (a) Explain four of the following elements of chess strategy: exploiting
        weaknesses, force, king safety, pawn structure, space, tempo, and clock
        management. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/kw5XkhM-DDI" target="_blank"
          >How To Identify and Exploit Weaknesses (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/6T-Dt1JwANM" target="_blank"
          >Only One Move Wins! (Understanding Forcing Moves) (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/4JzL_MWhK8o" target="_blank"
          >The Top 5 Priorities for Any Chess Opening! (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iPrSVMKHSgo" target="_blank"
          >Pawn Structures in Chess (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14391 mb-requirement-id-14393">
        (b) Explain any five of these chess tactics: clearance sacrifice, decoy,
        discovered attack, double check, double attack, fork, interposing,
        overloading, overprotecting, pin, skewer, remove the defender,
        zwischenzug, and zugzwang. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/yv7_0svOlQU" target="_blank"
          >Everything You Need to Know About Chess: Tactics &amp; Strategy!
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/vdS-uJoHS6g" target="_blank"
          >Every Chess Tactic Explained in 4 Minutes (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9cwNsRA3txY" target="_blank"
          >Decoy vs Deflection (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Yil3YavlOCo" target="_blank"
          >Interposing (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/_evjct0p6-c" target="_blank"
          >Zugzwang (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14391 mb-requirement-id-14394">
        (c) Set up a chessboard as follows and with White to move first,
        demonstrate how to force checkmate on the Black king:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14394 mb-requirement-id-14405">
        (1) White on <i>e1</i>, the White rooks on <i>a1</i> and <i>h1</i>, and
        the Black king on <i>e5</i>.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14394 mb-requirement-id-14406">
        (2) White King on <i>e1</i>, White queen on <i>d1</i>, Black king on
        <i>e5</i>.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14394 mb-requirement-id-14407">
        (3) White king on <i>e1</i>, White rook on <i>a1</i>, Black king on
        <i>e5</i>.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14391 mb-requirement-id-14395">
        (d) With White king on <i>d4</i>, White pawn on <i>e3</i>, and Black
        king on <i>e6</i>:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14395 mb-requirement-id-14408">
        (1) With White to move, demonstrate how White can force Black to allow
        his pawn to reach the last rank and be promoted to a queen.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14395 mb-requirement-id-14409">
        (2) With Black to move, demonstrate how Black can force a draw.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14391 mb-requirement-id-14410">
        (e) Set up and solve five direct-mate problems provided by your
        counselor.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14396">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      Explain to your counselor how chess tournaments are run, including the
      Swiss system tournament format, the round robin tournament format,
      pairings for each round, time controls, touch move, scoring, and chess
      ratings. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/b8oV2dj4dgU" target="_blank"
        >Why Swiss-Style Tournaments Are the BEST Tournaments! (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/5nTkIEmJE2o" target="_blank"
        >How To Use a Chess Clock (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/rKYsPvnm4eU" target="_blank"
        >Round Robin Tournament (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/NPM8py0xHi8" target="_blank"
        >How To Play: Touch Moves (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/86Is6YemsyA" target="_blank"
        >Chess Piece Values—How Much Is Each Chess Piece Worth? (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/o8AWrRk5su0" target="_blank"
        >How the Elo Rating System Works in Chess (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/AsYfbmp0To0" target="_blank"
        >The Elo Rating System for Math Nerds (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14411">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 7. </span>
      Do ONE of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14411 mb-requirement-id-14412">
        (a) Play at least three games of chess with other Scouts and/or your
        counselor. Replay the games from your score sheets and discuss with your
        counselor how you might have played each game differently.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14411 mb-requirement-id-14413">
        (b) Play in a scholastic (youth) chess tournament and use your score
        sheets from that tournament to replay your games with your counselor.
        Discuss with your counselor how you might have played each game
        differently.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-14411 mb-requirement-id-14414">
        (c) Organize and run a chess tournament with at least four players, plus
        you. Have each competitor play at least two games. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Chess/chess_tournament_chart_4_players.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Example Tournament Chart (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
</div>
